What honestly surprised me the most in this case is how normal everything felt in the beginning. There were no obvious warning signs—the buyer sounded polite, didn’t bargain, and everything seemed smooth and easy. It didn’t feel like a scam at all. That’s what made me realize that these situations don’t always look suspicious; sometimes they feel completely real, and that’s exactly how people get trapped.
After reading this, one habit I really want to change is reacting too quickly when it comes to online payments. Earlier, I might have just scanned a QR code or followed instructions without thinking much, especially if the other person seemed genuine. But now, I feel it’s really important to pause for a moment and think before doing anything.
This case made me understand that even a small action, like entering a UPI PIN without realizing, can lead to a big loss. So now, I just want to be more careful and not trust things online so easily.
